    %p The first person singular consists of the bare verbal stem featuring the I-Ablaut in the final syllable.
    %p The second person singular consists of the verbal stem plus the suffix <i>-s</i>. This is pronounced [s] after voiceless consonants and [z] everywhere else. If the stem ends in a coronal fricative, orthographically the form is regular, but an epenthetic [ɪ] is inserted between the stem and ending: <i>pîdsâ</i> “think” → <i>peidss</i> [ˈpejt.sɪs].
    %p The third person singular consists of the bare verbal stem with no ablaut. Consequently, the first and third person singulars are identical for most verbs if the stem cannot undergo I-Ablaut.</p>
    %p The first person plural consists of the verbal stem, a thematic vowel, and the ending <i>-ms</i>, pronounced [mz]. In the first, second, and fourth conjugations the thematic vowel is a stressed /a/, /e/, and /i/ respectively, while the verbal stem appears in its reduced grade. In the third conjugation, the stem appears in its full grade, but the thematic vowel is absent, and consequently an epenthetic [ɪ] is regularly inserted.
    %p The second person plural behaves just like the first person plural, only with the ending <i>-ts</i>.
    %p The third person plural adds the endings <i>-ô</i> (I/II), <i>-ê</i> (III), or <i>-iô</i> (IV) to the full grade of the verbal stem.
    %p Some of these endings can result in fully predictable spelling changes even though the pronunciation is completely regular. Notice above, for instance, how the stem for “recognize” varies between <i>*chenosc-</i> when by itself or before a consonant and <i>*chenosch-</i> when before a front vowel. Similarly, the stem for “need”, which is always pronounced /deb/ in the full grade, is spelled <i>*deb-</i> in monosyllabic forms (since graphical <i>e</i> in a monosyllable is always /e/) and <i>*déb-</i> in polysyllabic forms (since graphical <i>e</i> in polysyllabic forms is always /ə/). More generally, Tunisian spelling, at least as far as conjugation is concerned, generally opts for the most appropriate spelling for a given pronunciation, regardless of the spelling of other related forms.

  = section "Semi-Regular Forms" do
    %p Verbs that do not follow the regular pattern outlined in the previous section, but whose patterns can still be predicted based on the phonological structure of the stem, are known as semi-regular verbs or minor conjugations (as opposed to the four mentioned before, which are known as the major conjugations).

    = section "Stems Ending in /j/" do
      %p All verb stems ending in /j/ belong to Conjugation I. This was due to all /j/-final stems in other conjugations either shifting to Conjugation I by dissimilation or losing the /j/ entirely by assimilation, as it is much more salient before a back vowel (i.e., Cja) than before a front vowel (i.e., Cje or Cji). However, their conjugation seems to share some traits of both the A and I conjugations, due to this underlying /j/ vocalizing as /i/ in certain positions. The present tense of <i>źeliâ</i> “insult” is shown below.
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "źeliâ", :eng => "insult"},
        :forms         => %w(źéle źalis źale źelims źelits źaliê),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈðe.lə ˈðaː.liz ˈðaː.lə ðə.ˈlʲimz ðə.ˈlʲits ˈðaː.ljeː)

      %p In the first and third persons singular, the yod remains in place and vocalizes as /ə/. I-Ablaut still occurs in the first person singular, but on the preceding vowel.
      %p In the second person singular, first person plural, and second person plural, the yod vocalizes as /i/ (unstressed in 2Sg, stressed in 1Pl/2Pl). This results in the 1Pl and 2Pl forms superficially looking like Conjugation III forms, except unlike Conjugation III, the stem appears in a reduced grade.
      %p The third person plural is completely regular.

    = section "Stems Ending in /r/" do
      %p Tunisian prohibits coda /r/. There are three types of verbal stems where such an /r/ affects the present tense conjugation: stem-final /r/ after a vowel, as in <i>çirê</i> “want”; stem-final /r/ after a consonant, as in <i>comprâ</i> “compare”; and the so-called metathesizing /r/, as in <i>dremî</i> “sleep”.
      %p Stem-final /r/ after a vowel, as in <i>çirê</i> “want” (Conjugation III) is resolved in two ways. When word-final, the /r/ drops entirely, and the preceding vowel is lengthened if possible. Before a consonant, it is resolved through pleophony, the insertion of an epenthetic vowel afterwards that is dependent on the quality of the vowel preceding it. Specifically, if the preceding vowel is /a/, the epenthetic vowel is /ə/; if the preceding vowel is /e/ or /i/, the epenthetic vowel is /i/; and if the preceding vowel is /o/ or /u/, the epenthetic vowel is /o/. Diphthongs pattern as their nucleus and long vowels as their short counterparts. Thus, in the case of <i>çirê</i>, the stem becomes <i>*çî</i> word-finally and <i>*çiri-</i> before a consonant.
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "çirê", :eng => "want"},
        :forms         => %w(çî çiris çî çirims çirits çirô),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈʃiː ˈʃi.riz ˈʃiː ˈʃi.rimz ˈʃi.rits ˈʃi.rɔː)

      %p The metathesizing /r/ phonomenon occurs in stems that formerly had the structure *CVrC-, but that now alternate between *CrVC and *CVrVC. Examples include the verbs <i>dremî</i> “sleep” and <i>frevî</i> “boil”. These stems have the following three grades:
      %ul
        %li In the full grade, they take the form *CVrVC-, where the first V represents the original vowel and the second V is the pleophonic echo vowel as mentioned above. The full grade stems of these two verbs are <i>*dorom-</i> and <i>*fériv-</i>.
        %li Under I-Ablaut, they take the form *CVriC-, where the pleophonic vowel always surfaces as /i/. This likely suggests that at the time the I-Ablaut was first emerging, this pleophonic vowel was reduced and relatively indistinct, and was thus affected to a much greater extent by later front vowels than normal short vowels were. The I-Ablaut forms of these two verbs are <i>*dorim-</i> and <i>*fériv-</i>.
        %li In the reduced grade, they take the form *CrVC, where V represents the reduced counterpart of the full vowel. These forms were likely at one point also pleophonic, but stress-induced reductions caused the original pre-rhotic vowel to drop. The reduced grade forms of these two verbs are <i>*drem-</i> and <i>*frev-</i>.

      %p With these special graded forms in mind, it then becomes possible to conjugate these verbs regularly. Shown below is <i>dremî</i>:
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "dremî", :eng => "sleep"},
        :forms         => %w(dorim doroms dorom dremims dremits doromiô),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈdɔ.rim ˈdɔ.romz ˈdɔ.rom drə.ˈmimz drə.ˈmits dɔ.rɔ.ˈmjɔə)

      %p Verbs with stem-final /r/ after a consonant will be covered in section 4.5.2.5 as a case of final consonant clusters.

    = section "Stems Ending in /n/" do
      %p Tunisian also has restrictions on root-final /n/. Where /r/ drops with compensatory lengthening or acquires an epenthetic support vowel, /n/ tends to weaken to /j/, resulting in diphthongs word-internally or /iː/ word-finally. Shown below are the conjugations of <i>viçenê</i> “see” (II) and <i>pînâ</i> “fight” (I); the former is a typical /n/-final stem, while the latter shows the further vocalization of /j/ as /iː/ after diphthongs.
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "viçenê", :eng => "see"},
        :forms         => %w(viçî viçois viçî viçenéms viçenéts viçonê),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈvi.ʃiː ˈvi.ʃojz ˈvi.ʃiː vi.ʃə.ˈnʲɛmz vi.ʃə.ˈnʲɛts ˈvi.ʃɔ.neː)
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "pînâ", :eng => "fight"},
        :forms         => %w(poî poîs poî pînams pînats poinê),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈpɔ.jiː ˈpɔ.jiːz ˈpɔ.jiː piː.ˈnaːmz piː.ˈnaːts ˈpoj.neː)

    = section "Stems Containing Velar + Front Vowel" do
      %p Historically, Tunisian palatalized the velar stops /k g/ to /ʃ ʒ/ before stressed front vowels. This causes problems in verbal stems containing these sequences where the stress shifts on and off that particular front vowel, leading to a /k ~ ʃ/ or /g ~ ʒ/ alternation within the same verb paradigm. While these alternations still exist in some dialects (e.g., <i>çeî</i> “I eat” vs. <i>chenams</i> “we eat”), in the standard they have been levelled out in favor of the plosive. The following tables show the conjugation of <i>chîtâ</i> “sing” and <i>glâ</i> “freeze”.
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "chîtâ", :eng => "sing"},
        :forms         => %w(cheit cheits cheit chîtams chîtats cheitê),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈkejt ˈkejts ˈkejt kiː.ˈtaːmz kiː.ˈtaːts ˈkej.teː)
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "glâ", :eng => "freeze"},
        :forms         => %w(ghil ghels ghel glams glats ghélê),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈgil ˈgɛlz ˈgɛl ˈglaːmz ˈglaːts ˈge.leː)

      %p This sort of environment can also appear at the end of a stem, when the stem ends in /k g/ and is followed by a stressed front vowel. Here, the alternation is fully permissable, as apparently stem-final consonant changes are not considered as salient as stem-initial ones. Below is the conjugation of <i>leçê</i> “shine”:
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "leçê", :eng => "shine"},
        :forms         => %w(liuc lucs lucs leçéms leçéts luccê),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈljuk ˈluks ˈluk lə.ˈʃɛmz lə.ˈʃɛts ˈlu.keː)

    = section "Stems Ending in Consonant Clusters" do
      %p There are two types of semi-regular verbs with stems ending in consonant clusters: vowelless stems, where a historical vowel may sporadically reappear to break up the cluster, and true clustered stems, where an epenthetic vowel appears word-finally to support the cluster.
      %p Vowelless stems are verb stems that once ended in -CVC, but due to Tunisian vowel reduction, the vowel was lost in reduced-grade forms. This vowel will then reappear in full grade or I-Ablaut forms. Note that vowelless stems may actually contain vowels, and in fact often do; the name simply refers to the disappearing vowel in the stem. Examples include <i>yspê</i> “taste” (Conjugation II with full grade stem <i>*isap-</i>) and <i>ifchê</i> “cause” (Conjugation III with full grade stem <i>*éféc-</i>)#{footnote}.
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "yspê", :eng => "taste"},
        :forms         => %w(ysép ysaps ysap yspéms yspéts ysapê),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈi.sɛp ˈi.sʌps ˈi.sʌp is.ˈpɛmz is.ˈpɛts ˈi.sʌ.peː)
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "ifchê", :eng => "cause"},
        :forms         => %w(efic efécs eféc efécms efécts efécô),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈe.fik ˈe.fɛks ˈe.fɛk ˈe.fɛ.kɪmz ˈe.fɛ.kɪts ˈe.fe.kɔː)

      %p True clustered stems are stems that have always ended in a cluster, so there is no vowel to reappear in full grade forms. In these verbs, an epenthetic /ə/ is inserted at the end of the first person singular and third person singular forms, perhaps a faint remnant of the verb endings that were once present in Old Tunisian. Examples include <i>îtrâ</i> “enter” (I) and <i>solbê</i> “unlock” (III). Note that not all verb stems ending in clusters get this epenthetic vowel; many are completely regular, and will simply tolerate the word-final cluster. The distribution appears to reflect the phonotactics of an earlier form of Tunisian which was less tolerant of word-final clusters than the modern language.
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "îtrâ", :eng => "enter"},
        :forms         => %w(eitre eitrs eitre îtrams îtrats eitrê),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈej.trə ˈej.tɪrz ˈej.trə iː.ˈtraːmz iː.ˈtraːts ˈej.treː)
      = render 'present_tense',
        :verb          => {:tun => "solbê", :eng => "unlock"},
        :forms         => %w(sélbe solbs solbe solbms solbts solbê),
        :pronunciation => %w(ˈsʲɛl.bə ˈsolbz ˈsol.bə ˈsol.bɪmz ˈsol.bɪts ˈsol.beː)

  = section "Irregular Forms" do
    %p Of course, not all verbs have a predictable conjugation. Some are simply irregular, with paradigms that have to be memorized individually. Only two are completely exceptional: <i>istâ</i> “be” (which, interestingly, lacks third person forms) and <i>râ</i> “be (emphatic), really be”, which has an Arabic-derived conjugation.
    = render 'present_tense',
      :verb          => {:tun => "ystâ", :eng => "be"},
      :forms         => ["som", "es", nil, "sums", "ests", nil],
      :pronunciation => ["ˈsom", "ˈɛs", nil, "ˈsumz", "ˈɛsts", nil]
    = render 'present_tense',
      :verb          => {:tun => "râ", :eng => "be (emphatic)"},
      :forms         => %w(râne râc râ rânâ râcm râm),
      :pronunciation => %w(ˈraː.nə ˈraːk ˈraː ˈraː.naː ˈraː.kɪm ˈraːm)

    %p The present tense of <i>ystâ</i> is actually the only irregular conjugation preserved from Latin. All other irregular Latin present tense verbs were regularized or lost on the way to modern Tunisian. However, a number of new verbs have become irregular. These include <i>loâ</i> “take”, <i>unî</i> “go”, <i>vivê</i> “live”, <i>ebê</i> “have”, and <i>yddâ</i> “give”.
